3118,IssuesEvent,2018-07-31 11:52:53+00:00,94218531,lanpa/tensorboardX,4235319,andres-fr,,,closed,imagepy import error handling message is deceiving,[],[],2,"As I describe here:

https://stackoverflow.com/a/51592268/4511978

Importing `imagepy`with missing dependencies can raise ImportErrors *for some of the submodules only*. Regarding tensorboardX, these errors are handled in writer.py:

https://github.com/lanpa/tensorboardX/blob/master/tensorboardX/summary.py#L273

But the message (`""add_video needs package moviepy""`) is deceiving, since it is possible to have `moviepy` installed and still get `ImportError`s. In my case, `moviepy` loaded well, but loading `moviepy.editor` failed. I fixed it installing the `requests` package.

-------

Regarding possible solutions, different approaches are possible, and I'm not sure to what extent this is `moviepy`'s or `tensorboardX`'s fault... maybe a more general error message? or first importing `moviepy` only and then importing the editor, each one of them with their own `try...except` and specific message like this?:

```python
def make_video(tensor, fps):
    try:
        import moviepy.editor as mpy
    except ImportError:
        print('add_video needs package moviepy')
        return
    try:
        from moviepy import editor as mpy
    except ImportError:
        print(""moviepy is installed, but can't import moviepy.editor. Some dependencies could be missing [imageio, requests]"")
        return
    import tempfile
```",{},{}
