8757,IssuesEvent,2018-08-30 17:25:59+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,605277,uranusjr,647025,pypa,closed,Indeterminate order generates unneccessary diffs in Pipfile.lock when upgrading.,[],[],1,"My `Pipfile.lock` contains many lines of the following form:

    ""markers"": ""python_version != '3.2.*' and python_version != '3.0.*' and python_version != '3.1.*' and python_version >= '2.7' and python_version != '3.3.*'"",

and after an unrelated change, this line is changed into

    ""markers"": ""python_version != '3.0.*' and python_version != '3.2.*' and python_version != '3.3.*' and python_version != '3.1.*' and python_version >= '2.7'"",

i.e. the same content but different order. It would be great to keep the order deterministic in order to keep the diffs small when updating.
",{},{}
8771,IssuesEvent,2018-04-24 23:36:28+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,954310,techalchemy,647025,pypa,closed,Support for multiple environment files?,[],[],1,"This is a feature request, not a bug, so I'm not using the template. I searched the open/closed issues for mention of this, but couldn't find anything. If this request already exists, I apologize.

I would like for pipenv to support multiple environment files, a la [Honcho](https://github.com/nickstenning/honcho) and [Foreman](http://ddollar.github.io/foreman/). For many workflows I'm aware of, it's beneficial to have a default `.env` file checked in to the repository, along with `.env.local` files on developer machines, with secrets and such. Based on my reading of the docs (and no further digging, sorry), pipenv doesn't seem to support this. Could it?
",{},{}
8778,IssuesEvent,2018-04-26 11:26:52+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,605277,uranusjr,647025,pypa,closed,Pipfile line endings changed after install,[],[],5,"When a package is installed pipenv rewrites the Pipfile but doesn't retain line endings.  This test is in Linux but I noticed it first in Windows.  We keep lines with LF in Git but Pipenv changed it to CRLF.  I would think that matching existing line endings and using native for a new file would be proper, but for me it'd be fine to just always use LF.

