8811,IssuesEvent,2016-05-21 14:19:49+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,Easy_install would mess up the order of sys.path in develop install,[],[],1,"Environment:

Setuptools 20.6.7
Ubuntu server 14.04 within VirtualBox

**Background**:

Debian alike has two paths for python packages, one is for packages managed by apt `/usr/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/`, the other is for packages managed by pip or other 3rd-party software `/usr/local/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/`. Usually, the latter holds newer packages, so it's placed before the former.

**Issue**
After performing a `python setup.py develop`, I found that all projects crashed with something like ImportError. After some research, it seems to me that in develop install easy_setup would add current project's and its dependencies' paths into an `easy_setup.pth` file in order to modify `sys.path`. However if a package is located in `/usr/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/`, easy_setup would still add this path into `easy_setup.pth`, which would cause this path place prior to `/usr/local/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/` and lead those disasters.


My temporary workaround  is to move dependencies located in `/usr/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/` to `/usr/local/lib/python*.*/dist-packages/`.

Hope you can fix this, it has spent me lots of time to discover where the problem is.

Regards.",{},{}
8812,IssuesEvent,2017-04-19 03:54:54+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,Tests failing on Nightly Python builds,[],[],1,"Starting in [this build](https://travis-ci.org/pypa/setuptools/builds/222357603), the tests seem to have started failing on the nightly builds, presumably due to a change in them.",{},{}
8825,IssuesEvent,2018-01-04 11:28:32+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,Generated scripts can be written in a bogus encoding,[],[],3,"https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/blob/118edbb2b715c96620b51018c1d28e81f2318053/setuptools/command/easy_install.py#L836-L837

[`open`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#open)'s `encoding` argument, when unspecified, uses [`locale.getpreferredencoding
`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/locale.html#locale.getpreferredencoding), which is not necessarily UTF-8. However, the generated script doesn't include an encoding cookie and can contain non-ASCII data if, say, the shebang path contains non-ASCII components. Either always open the file with `encoding='utf-8'` or write out an encoding cookie.

This has resulted in an issue filed on a different project: https://github.com/pypa/pipenv/issues/1265
",{},{}
8827,IssuesEvent,2016-12-11 23:47:40+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,setuptools.compat,[],[],1,"Hi, this is a question - not an issue.

I have some older code that use the following import:

    from setuptools.compat import reraise

which now gives:

    ImportError: No module named 'setuptools.compat'

This code did work earlier so I assume something has changed in setuptools - or is there something else missing ? Searching this project I see a `def reraise` in _setuptools/pkg_resources/_vendor/six.py_. The path made it seemed a bit ""internal"". What is the correct way to import this now ?",{},{}
