9023,IssuesEvent,2016-12-01 08:17:05+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,608607,tobad357,779641,Parsely,opened,Support ListGroupRequest/ListGroupResponse commands in protocol,[],[],0,"Hi
I haven't had time to write up a proper pull request. 
In the meantime if someone wants to use these for checking on lag or listing consumer groups go ahead. Add the two classes below to your code and then

```
req_handler = self.connect(broker.host, broker.port, self.handler)
future = req_handler.request(ListGroupRequest())
res = future.get(ListGroupResponse)

for group in res.groups:
   print group
```

Please note that you need to connect to all brokers to get the consumer groups
Also Kafka doesn't show consumer groups that are currently not connected
I believe this will be fixed in a later version of kafka

```
class ListGroupRequest(Request):
    """"""A list group request

    Specification::

    ListGroupsRequest =>
    """"""
    @property
    def API_KEY(self):
        """"""API_KEY for this request, from the Kafka docs""""""
        return 16

    def get_bytes(self):
        """"""Create a new list group request""""""
        output = bytearray(self.HEADER_LEN)
        self._write_header(output)
        return output


class ListGroupResponse(Response):
    """"""A list group response

    Specification::

    ListGroupsResponse => ErrorCode Groups
      ErrorCode => int16
      Groups => [GroupId ProtocolType]
        GroupId => string
        ProtocolType => string
    """"""
    error = None
    groups = None

    def __init__(self, buff):
        """"""Deserialize into a new Response

        :param buff: Serialized message
        :type buff: :class:`bytearray`
        """"""
        fmt = 'h [SS]'
        response = struct_helpers.unpack_from(fmt, buff, 0)

        error, groups = response
        self.error = error
        self.groups = []
        for group_name,_ in groups:
            self.groups.append(group_name)
```",{},{}
9025,IssuesEvent,2018-01-04 18:58:01+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,it's better to identify which partitioner in producer doc,[],[],0,"**PyKafka version**: latest
**Kafka version**:  any

if initing a produce without specifying partitioner, pykafka will use RandomPartitioner rather than HashingPartitioner to identify partion_id, no matter setting an unnull partition_key or not.

this leads msg with same partition_key sended to random partition,  which is unexpected.

=============
i think it's necessary to notice this feature in document.




  ",{},{}
9027,IssuesEvent,2017-05-11 22:07:51+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,Reset offset for unowned partitions in balanced consumer group,"[{'id': 8945345, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 360183304, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '006b75', 'default': True}]",[],6,"I want to be able to make all consumers in a consumer group go ""back in time"". That is, I have a balanced consumer group that has been running for a while, but I need it to reprocess some range of messages that are present in Kafka as if it hadn't seen them before. (note: this is _not_ the same as auto_reset, where you're creating the offsets for the first time if they aren't present.)

The obvious way to do this is:

```
    # find the partitions that we need to reset
    topic = kafka.topics[topic_name]
    partitions = topic.partitions.values()

    # build a consumer to get access to the consumer group API
    consumer = topic.get_balanced_consumer(consumer_group=""consumer_group_name"")

    consumer.reset_offsets(
        [(partition, epoch_timestamp*1000)
         for partition in partitions])
```

However, this throws an exception:

```
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/pykafka/balancedconsumer.py"", line 671, in reset_offsets
    self._consumer.reset_offsets(partition_offsets=partition_offsets)
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/pykafka/simpleconsumer.py"", line 593, in reset_offsets
    raise KafkaException(""Unknown partition supplied to reset_offsets\n%s"", e)
pykafka.exceptions.KafkaException: ('Unknown partition supplied to reset_offsets\n%s', KeyError(<pykafka.partition.Partition at 0x7f196afc55d0 (id=0)>,))
```

That's because SimpleConsumer is trying to [""turn Partitions into their corresponding OwnedPartitions""](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/e18bdeb3586fab21493b755d564d6b4aa8ec7ef2/pykafka/simpleconsumer.py#L627). But I want to reset the stored offset in Zookeeper for Partitions that I don't own and that other consumers may currently be processing.

It may be okay for me to just take ownership of all of the partitions, reset the offsets, and then relinquish ownership so the other consumers in the group resume from wherever I reset them to. But I don't see a straight forward way to do that in pykafka's API.

**PyKafka version**: 2.1.2
**Kafka version**: 0.8.2
",{},{}
9051,IssuesEvent,2016-09-24 02:45:10+00:00,68484371,cs50/submit50,14919101,nhawke,788676,cs50,opened,GitHub Releases not split up if there are extra .c files,[],[],0,"See the following submit50 repos for examples of this happening for pset2:

