9291,IssuesEvent,2017-04-17 16:27:20+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,326528,oxtopus,1039191,numenta,opened,Improve version reporting,[],[],0,"nupic should have a first-clas API for reporting version details, including its nupic.bindings dependency.  Something like the following would be very helpful:

```python
>>> nupic.version()
'0.7.0.dev0'
>>> nupic.getNupicBindingsDependency()
'0.6.2.dev0'
>>> nupic.bindings.version()
'0.6.2.dev0'
```

This way, users may self report installed versions and compare.  Even better if there were a way to determine commit sha, too, if installed from source.",{},{}
9297,IssuesEvent,2017-05-08 19:00:08+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,opened,HTMPredictionModel sets/gets anomaly params incorrectly,[],[],0,"HTMPredictionModel calls [`setParameter`](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/c89603223b5c34f17b5d788cab5295038efab8d4/src/nupic/frameworks/opf/htm_prediction_model.py#L317) and [`getParameter`](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/c89603223b5c34f17b5d788cab5295038efab8d4/src/nupic/frameworks/opf/htm_prediction_model.py#L325) on its anomaly classifier improperly (does not include the `index` argument). The interface for ``PyRegion`` is:

    PyRegion.setParameter(self, name, index, value)
    PyRegion.getParameter(self, name, index)

I don't see where these set/get calls are made within our codebase, so I don't think they are being tested.",{},{}
9301,IssuesEvent,2015-01-05 23:57:50+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,8323700,BoltzmannBrain,1039191,numenta,opened,Anomaly filtering bug testing,[],[],0,anomaly_likelihood_test.py needs tests to cover/expose the filtering bug (false negatives; issue #1722).,{},{}
9302,IssuesEvent,2015-02-27 18:31:43+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,opened,Update main NuPIC README with howto install on Windows,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'fef2c0'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/windows', 'name': 'windows', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],0,,{},{}
9326,IssuesEvent,2016-02-15 16:03:43+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,closed,Filters documentation and testing,[],[],1,"[Filters](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/src/nupic/data/filters.py) are used in the RecordSensor region but it's unclear what a filter is, let alone how to apply a filter. There's a [unit test for filters](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/tests/unit/nupic/data/filters_test.py), but it's unclear what is being tested. We should improve the documentation by improving the testing, and adding a docstring to the [DeltaFilter class](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/src/nupic/data/filters.py#L98).",{},{}
9329,IssuesEvent,2016-07-28 17:27:38+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,closed,Renaming nupic to nupic.python,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/priority:3', 'name': 'priority:3', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/type:administrative', 'name': 'type:administrative', 'color': '006b75'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/under-review', 'name': 'under-review', 'color': 'fbca04'}]","[{'login': 'rhyolight', 'id': 15566, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/15566?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/rhyolight', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/rhyolight/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",19,"This issue matches the extraction plan (https://github.com/numenta/nupic/wiki/nupic.core-Extraction-Plan).

The plan above is very clear about `nupic.core` being just a transitional repo in the moment, in the end it will have all features located in `nupic` at moment (sensors, encoders, frameworks, etc).

I think this renaming should be done as soon as possible because the terms `nupic.core` and `nupic` already confused me and probally confused others, making I suggest incorrect and non-sense naming based on misunderstoods like seen here: https://github.com/numenta/nupic/issues/724. 

Because this misunderstood, I also suggested the name `nupic.core.net` to the bindings repository to the .Net platform. However based on the extraction plan, I should call it simply `nupic.bindings.net`.

This issue do not imply changes in the current internal structure, i.e. all namespace should continue being `nupic`. Futhermore, the most changes already were done like the default strucuture for pyhton projects and now the ""pip installabe"" feature which will be merged soon. Probally some minor changes should be done in `nupic.tools` or others.

**update:**
@scottpurdy suggested we renamed it to `nupic.python` in order to we follow the ""project.subproject"" notation.",{},{}
9333,IssuesEvent,2015-12-09 14:56:33+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,2166111,breznak,1039191,numenta,opened,AnomalyScore and multiStepPredictions.N in OPF do not have correct (strict) data type (can be None),"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/subject:opf', 'name': 'subject:opf', 'color': 'c7def8'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/type:bug', 'name': 'type:bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],0,"* `anomalyScore` is defined as a float in range [0..1], while in OPF results file it has type ""string"" (because a few 1st values can be `None`)
* that is because `(multistep)prediction models` predict the 1st N values as `None`, instead of desired data type again. 

This could be easily fixed, anomalyScore should be `0.5` during burn-in, predictions could be eg `0.0`. 
That is a more correct approach, supports strict typing, and some applications could be easier. 

Our simple use-case is in https://github.com/nupic-community/nupic.visualizations/issues/30 
",{},{}
9349,IssuesEvent,2015-09-02 15:45:11+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,239726,scottpurdy,1039191,numenta,opened,Run Python tests with py.test --pyargs,[],[],0,"When running tests directly from the repo, there is a risk of a version mismatch with the installed version of the Python package. `py.test` provides the `--pyargs` option to specify a Python package rather than a file system path. We should use this option in Travis and recommend it in our documentation.",{},{}
9352,IssuesEvent,2017-02-15 16:23:13+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,5755530,arhik,1039191,numenta,opened,typo in CHANGELOG.md 'maxBoost' -> 'boostStrength',[],[],0,,{},{}
