10032,IssuesEvent,2018-07-27 11:50:06+00:00,14437755,getsentry/responses,65913,rbu,1396951,getsentry,opened,"Requesting a URL, then changing the response will return the old response",[],[],0,"The documentation states:
> You can also add multiple responses for the same url: ....

However, this is not true if you interleave adding and requesting responses:
```py
>>> import responses
>>> import requests
>>> 
>>> responses.start()
>>> 
>>> responses.add(responses.GET, ""https://example.com/"",
...     json={'response': 'old'}
... )
>>> requests.get('https://example.com/').content
b'{""response"": ""old""}'
>>> 
>>> responses.add(responses.GET, ""https://example.com/"",
...     json={'response': 'new'}
... )
>>> 
>>> 
>>> requests.get('https://example.com/').content
b'{""response"": ""old""}'
>>> requests.get('https://example.com/').content
b'{""response"": ""new""}'
>>> requests.get('https://example.com/').content
b'{""response"": ""new""}'
```

Expected result: After adding the ""new"" response, a ""new"" response is returned in the subsequent request.

Requests version: '2.19.1', Python 3.6.6",{},{}
10045,IssuesEvent,2017-02-21 10:44:58+00:00,2527828,getsentry/raven-python,665072,bittner,1396951,getsentry,opened,Refactor captureException -> capture_exception (camelCase vs. snake_case),[],[],0,"(I know this  is maybe a low-priority issue compare to all the other 112, at the moment. Sorry in advance!)

I've happily seen in the source code that the camel case [`captureException` is deprecated](https://github.com/getsentry/raven-python/blob/master/raven/base.py#L872-L876) in the base implementation.

However, the Django docs still [instruct to use](https://docs.sentry.io/clients/python/integrations/django/#setup) `client.captureException()` ([source](https://github.com/getsentry/raven-python/blob/master/docs/integrations/django.rst#setup)). Is there a reason for this?

I'd really like to use pythonic code wherever I can.

Disclaimer
----------
I must admit, I have not invested more that a few minutes to figure out which code does exactly what. I've seen it's a bit complicated, probably for historical reasons (`client` is in `raven.contrib.django.models`, which is imported by `raven.contrib.django.raven_compat.models`).

I would guess this is really something that only needs to be fixed in the docs, but I'm really not sure what the history or technical background of the code snippets in the Django-related docs actually is. 

It would be nice though, to have camel case replaced by snake case for pythonic code style. Not sure whether you run flake8 or pylint over the code base every once in a while. I'm not seeing any related configuration in the project root. It's probably not the top priority atm.",{},{}
