10638,IssuesEvent,2017-08-18 09:50:45+00:00,58059785,zalando/expan,4135248,shansfolder,1564818,zalando,closed,Default Parameters of Constructor of Experiment class,[],[],2,"In the class expan.core.experiment.Experiment, the constructor starts with the following:

def __init__(self, control_variant_name, data, metadata, report_kpi_names=[], derived_kpis=[]):

It is not a good idea to have mutable values (i.e. empty list) as the default parameter value because Python does not create a new empty list for you every time you create an object. Instead, it creates it only once and then, it will reference to the same list every time so the next time you create an Experiment object, it is possible that a non-empty list is passed to the function. 

I suggest to replace the square brackets by ""None"". And then, inside the function
if report_kpi_names is None:
    report_kpi_names = list()

In that case, it can guarantee an empty list for the function. 

Details of this problem can be found: http://docs.python-guide.org/en/latest/writing/gotchas/",{},{}
10650,IssuesEvent,2016-09-29 13:27:43+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,719860,trifthen,1564818,zalando,closed,Postgres timeline needlessly advanced during startup of primary node,[],[],5,"It appears Patroni considers every Postgres shutdown a fatal crash. 

In the event an existing cluster is started following a controlled shutdown, Patroni always creates a `recovery.conf` file, even when no recovery is necessary. This advances the internal instance timeline, as Postgres assumes an uncontrolled shutdown and executes the full recovery stack.

To prevent this, Patroni should:

1. Obtain the primary lock, if possible.
2. Lock obtained, attempt to start Postgres without recovery mechanisms.
3. If Postgres starts normally, no further action is taken.
4. If Postgres will not start or reports an error necessitating recovery, create a `recovery.conf` file and follow the current protocol.
",{},{}
10661,IssuesEvent,2016-08-29 10:54:12+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,64938,ants,1564818,zalando,opened,Replication slot creation fails when name contains a dash,[],[],0,"PostgreSQL replication slots names can only contain \[a-z0-9_\]. When trying to use hostname containing a dash or period as name, this creates the following exception on the master:

    ERROR: Exception when changing replication slots
    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File ""/opt/app/patroni/lib/python2.7/site-packages/patroni/postgresql.py"", line 921, in sync_replication_slots
    WHERE slot_name = %s)"""""", slot, slot)
    File ""/opt/app/patroni/lib/python2.7/site-packages/patroni/postgresql.py"", line 320, in query
    return self.retry(self._query, sql, *params)
    File ""/opt/app/patroni/lib/python2.7/site-packages/patroni/utils.py"", line 292, in __call__
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
    File ""/opt/app/patroni/lib/python2.7/site-packages/patroni/postgresql.py"", line 313, in _query
    raise e
    ProgrammingError: replication slot name ""patroni-n2"" contains invalid character
    HINT:  Replication slot names may only contain lower case letters, numbers, and the underscore character.

On the standby PostgreSQL fails to start up with the error `pg_ctl: could not start server`.

I think we should do one of:

1. Skip creating slots for invalid names.
2. Detect name containing invalid characters at startup and show a nicer error message.
3. Same as 2. but only when use_slots: true
4. Replace invalid characters with underscores when calculating the slot name.

I'm somewhat partial to 4 because I'd like to simplify the initial setup procedure to use hostname as name. This does create the danger of slot names colliding with names differing only in invalid characters, e.g. unicode names. Creating a replication slot name reservation mechanism in the DCS just for this issue seems kind of overkill. 2 seems like a no-go because it will break existing installs when upgrading.

Thoughts?",{},{}
10675,IssuesEvent,2018-04-05 15:59:22+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,339913,alexeyklyukin,1564818,zalando,opened,Allow a HA cluster to run in a standby mode ,[],[],0,"Right now, Patroni always promotes one node in a cluster that acquires the leader lock.

We may want to have a standby cluster, running alongside the primary one (i.e. in another datacenter) and consisting of only standby nodes, replicating from the primary one. Such cluster will have no master, there will be one ""main"" replica replicating from the master in the primary cluster, and all the other cascading replicas replicating from the main one.

We can already achieve this by writing a permanent leader and member keys in DCS, specifying the address of the cluster in the member key. However, the primary leader knows nothing about the standby cluster, it doesn't create a replication slot, and the whole setup requires direct access to DCS from the user implementing it.

What we can do is to create a new key in DCS called standby, holding connection string for the actual master inside. When this key is there, the leader key will be interpreted as a pointer to the main replica, instead of the master, that replica will not promote itself, and the other replicas will replicate from the main one. When the standby key disappears, the cluster stops being a standby, and the replica holding the leader key will promote itself.

From the user point of view, there is not much additional information to be supplied to Patroni. We only need the credentials for the master (standby and superuser names and passwords, they are already required in the current configuration file and obviously should match between the primary and the standby cluster) and the connection string.",{},{}
