11817,IssuesEvent,2016-02-12 02:08:19+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,pants hangs when too much output,[],[],1,"The excellent @dhelder writes:

```
I have a misbehaving program outputting garbage at 100 lines per second, 1 million characters per line. When I run it, I never see any output on stderr. However, lines are logged to disk .pants.d/runs.

Expected behavior: anything logged to disk should also be logged to stdout/stderr. Preferably stdout/stderr first.

In in pants.java.excecutor:spawn, I add ""subprocess_args['stderr'] = sys.stderr"", then it works. So the problem is probably related to FileBackedRWBuf.

It'd be nice to be able to disable storing run output to disk. In fact, maybe it's not desirable at all due. (Make sense for build tasks.)
```

He provided a nice demo. Its pants-repo equivalent: 

```
$ git diff
diff --git a/examples/src/scala/com/pants/example/JvmRunExample.scala b/examples/src/scala/com/pants/example/JvmRunExample.scala
index 287ffcb..17acc35 100644
--- a/examples/src/scala/com/pants/example/JvmRunExample.scala
+++ b/examples/src/scala/com/pants/example/JvmRunExample.scala
@@ -11,5 +11,10 @@ object JvmRunExample {
   def main(args: Array[String]) {
     println(""Hello, World"")
     println(""args: "" + args.mkString("", ""))
+
+   while (true) {
+      Console.err.println(""A"" * 1000000)
+      Thread.sleep(10)
+    }
   }
 }
```

and then 

$ ./pants goal list examples/src/scala/com/pants/example:jvm-run-example

",{},{}
