11967,IssuesEvent,2017-07-31 08:24:57+00:00,7695747,wal-e/wal-e,10639,andruby,3310438,wal-e,opened,backup-push to S3 sometimes fails due to XAmzContentSHA256Mismatch,[],[],0,"We've been running WAL-E for over a year. The backup-push is run via cron every Sunday morning and has successfully finished every time, until about a month ago. The last 8 weeks, the backup-push was successful 3 times and failed 5 times, at different progress points:

|Date|File count|Success|
|----|----|---|
| Jun 11 | 922 files | OK |
| Jun 18 | 932 files | OK |
| Jun 25 | 395 files | FAILED |
| Jul 2  | 795 files | FAILED |
| Jul 9  | 994 files | OK |
| Jul 16 | 296 files | FAILED |
| Jul 23 | 831 files | FAILED |
| Jul 30 | 694 files | FAILED |

Because our logs had already been rotated, I only have the error messages of the last 2 failures.

```xml
<Error>
    <Code>XAmzContentSHA256Mismatch</Code>
    <Message>The provided 'x-amz-content-sha256' header does not match what was computed.</Message>
    <ClientComputedContentSHA256>8487d1d6ff0c4e33e98ec90cf60af5481afefdae958b47fc47966968ca97a036</ClientComputedContentSHA256>
    <S3ComputedContentSHA256>316b6f3685fc0c5036f539eaad85230c359c237088b5419584b11661845ff587</S3ComputedContentSHA256>
    <RequestId>1C64..snipped..F3FD0</RequestId>
    <HostId>9y6XGqv..snipped..wIrF0Y=</HostId>
</Error
```

Python error in log:

```
Jul 30 08:21:53 database wal_e.main   CRITICAL MSG: An unprocessed exception has avoided all error handling#012        DETAIL: Traceback (most recent call last):#012          File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/wal_e/cmd.py"", line 578, in main#012            pool_size=args.pool_size)#012          File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/wal_e/operator/backup.py"", line 197, in database_backup#012            **kwargs)#012          File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/wal_e/operator/backup.py"", line 502, in _upload_pg_cluster_dir#012            pool.put(tpart)#012          File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/wal_e/worker/upload_pool.py"", line 108, in put#012            self._wait()#012          File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/wal_e/worker/upload_pool.py"", line 65, in _wait#012            raise val#012        S3ResponseError: S3ResponseError: 400 Bad Request#012        <?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""UTF-8""?>#012        <Error><Code>XAmzContentSHA256Mismatch</Code><Message>The provided 'x-amz-content-sha256' header does not match what was computed.</Message><ClientComputedContentSHA256>8487d1d6ff0c4e33e98ec90cf60af5481afefdae958b47fc47966968ca97a036</ClientComputedContentSHA256><S3ComputedContentSHA256>316b6f3685fc0c5036f539eaad85230c359c237088b5419584b11661845ff587</S3ComputedContentSHA256><RequestId>1C64..snipped..F3FD0</RequestId><HostId>9y6XGqv..snipped..wIrF0Y=</HostId></Error>#012        #012        STRUCTURED: time=2017-07-30T06:21:53.479073-00 pid=32748
```

It seems like somewhere bit(s) get flipped between WAL-E computing the files' sha256 and Amazon computing it. I don't know wether the flip occurs on our disk, the network or Amazon.

Is there a way to find out where the flip would have occurred? Can WAL-E be configured to retry sending the backup part?",{},{}
