12341,IssuesEvent,2017-07-17 17:24:51+00:00,53143022,oduwsdl/ipwb,2514780,machawk1,4416806,oduwsdl,closed,"Prep for ipwb demo at IPFS all-hands on July 17, 2017","[{'id': 559956153, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/oduwsdl/ipwb/labels/Meta', 'name': 'Meta', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}]",[],17,"Per https://twitter.com/daviddias/status/881969834409545730, @diasdavid invited us to demo ipwb at the IPFS all-hands. We ought to outline the best way to demo the software. For reference, below is the demo we originally planned for WAC2017 in London in June. For brevity during the presentation, we were unable to show all of the steps.

1. Show live page: http://www.cs.odu.edu/~salam/
1. Login to ws-dl-02, cd ~/public_html/ipwb
1. ws-dl-02: ipwb index ipwb/samples/warcs/salam.warc > (cdxj)
1. Show (cdxj) in terminal 
1. ws-dl-02: ipwb replay (cdxj)
1. Show wac.cdxj on web browser
1. Download to disk (desktop)
1. Local: ipwb replay (cdxj)
1. Show in browser locally
1. ipfs cat (hash from cdxj)
1. Go to https://ipfs.io/ipfs/(hash)",{},{}
12356,IssuesEvent,2015-07-16 14:13:46+00:00,17710133,googleads/googleads-python-lib,13366838,btourtellott,4551618,googleads,opened,Inconsistent partial error handling with Ads Py Google,[],[],0,"One difference between Google Ads and Ads Py Google is when sending a mutate operation with the “partial failure” (https://github.com/googleads/googleads-python-lib/blob/master/googleads/adwords.py L190) option set to true. In Ads Py Google, the returned Python dictionary would have the key “value” which is a list of all the successful mutated entities. Any unsuccessful mutated entities are omitted from this list, and included in the list keyed by “partialFailureErrors”. In Google Ads, the returned Python Suds object has the attribute “value”, which returns a list of the successful mutated entities, but includes an empty “suds.sax.text.Text” field as a placeholder for where the entities that did not mutate successfully occurred. Basically in Ads Py Google, they were omitted from “value”, but in Google Ads they have a placeholder in “value”.
 
Are you guys aware of this difference? I am curious if this is expected behavior, and if it is something that we should expect going forward.
",{},{}
12361,IssuesEvent,2018-01-09 15:29:59+00:00,17710133,googleads/googleads-python-lib,6739520,msaniscalchi,4551618,googleads,closed,adwords module takes up a lot of CPU power,[],[],2,"Hi, 
I'm trying to deploy a web app that includes the AdWords module, the current server is rather small, however 1 call to the adwords api takes up ~90% of CPU power, using the code example for targeting ideas. Is this normal, or am i missing some configuration of some sort?",{},{}
12384,IssuesEvent,2016-11-03 07:26:40+00:00,32479278,juju/theblues,6012845,jujugui,4604548,juju,closed,API version should be set by the library instead of supplied by user,[],[],0,"The comments and repo summary say to use v4 of the API, but, as reported in #43, that now fails with the current version of this library.

The library should have the supported API version in the code, instead of relying on it being provided by the user, so that a given release will always reference the API version that it works with.
",{},{}
12385,IssuesEvent,2016-03-23 22:57:26+00:00,12898486,juju/charm-tools,246944,chuckbutler,4604548,juju,opened,charm-tools as of 2.0 pulls in x11,[],[],0,"This appears to be due to mercurial pulling in tcl, which pulls in x11. 

These recommends directives are bloating our tooling and imagery with x11-common, tcl, and other depends we don't need. Can we change these to --no-recommends, or perhaps consider another method to reduce the overall incoming packages?",{},{}
12387,IssuesEvent,2017-10-02 20:11:59+00:00,12898486,juju/charm-tools,70613,marcoceppi,4604548,juju,closed,"Minor error with ""charm build"" in a gnu screen session",[],[],3,"## Checklist

 - [X] Confirmed this is an issue with charm-tools, not charmstore-client
 - [X] Provide versions of tools used
 - [X] Described the feature or ways to replicate the issue

## What version am I running?

I ran the following command: `charm version` and got the following ouput:

```
charm 2.2.2
charm-tools 2.1.2
```

I am using: ubuntu/xenial

When run ""charm build"" in a Gnu Screen session, it fails with the following error:
```

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/snap/charm/17/bin/charm-build"", line 11, in <module>
    load_entry_point('charm-tools==2.1.2', 'console_scripts', 'charm-build')()
  File ""/snap/charm/17/lib/python2.7/site-packages/charmtools/build/builder.py"", line 671, in main
    configLogging(build)
  File ""/snap/charm/17/lib/python2.7/site-packages/charmtools/build/builder.py"", line 579, in configLogging
    blessings.Terminal(),
  File ""/snap/charm/17/lib/python2.7/site-packages/blessings/__init__.py"", line 105, in __init__
    self._init_descriptor)
_curses.error: setupterm: could not find terminal
```

This is not difficult to work around. I inspected the value of TERM in my environment, and saw that it was ""screen.xterm-256color"". I changed the value of TERM to ""xterm-256color"", and the command worked. It would be nicer if the tool simply ignored the ""screen."" part of a terminal declaration, however.",{},{}
