   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:39       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0x952e@18.188.70.61)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:40       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0x38b0@136.179.11.188)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:40       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0x6914@35.172.216.29)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xb969@47.52.27.7)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xc496@40.84.48.167)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xcde6@13.95.123.161)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0x590b@103.75.0.132)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xfede@89.38.99.153)>
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:41       chain  Got Receipts for 19 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0x3aaf@47.88.228.205)>

# Here all coroutines above completed: 3s 
   DEBUG  07-21 08:43:44       chain  Got block receipts for chain segment

# Now we combine the downloaded bodies with the headers and persist them to the DB: 
# https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/4b3e30b4edf0e3ca0b6ddd48dca469dfa8115c52/p2p/chain.py#L378
# This runs on the main thread, but the heavy lifting is done in the DB process
   
# This would mean ~4s on all 192 ChainDB.coro_persist_block() calls
   INFO  07-21 08:43:48       chain  Imported 192 headers in 14.43 seconds, new head: #3920123
```

So, ~1s to download bodies, ~2s to download receipts and ~12 to process/persist them.",{},{}
13114,IssuesEvent,2018-02-01 18:23:45+00:00,77478378,ethereum/py-evm,824194,pipermerriam,6250754,ethereum,closed,Read-only property decorator,[],[],3,"### What is wrong?
See https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/pull/273#discussion_r161866203
In `ExecutionContext` (evm.vm.execution_context) and `TransactionContext` (#327), it's better to write an explicit decorator `read_only_property` or `immutable_property` which includes a setter that raises such an `AttributeError` when someone try to modify these properties.

### How can it be fixed
1. Write the decorator in [eth-utils](https://github.com/ethereum/eth-utils) or a new file `evm/utils/decorators.py`
2. Update the decorator of `ExecutionContext` and `TransactionContext`
",{},{}
13132,IssuesEvent,2018-03-18 11:13:05+00:00,77478378,ethereum/py-evm,3684187,onyb,6250754,ethereum,opened,Move make_receipt to BaseTransactionExecutor,[],[],0,"### What is wrong?

#383 was recently merged, bringing a generic transaction executor to be used as mixin in different VM state classes, thereby allowing us to achieve better code reuse across forks.

A good candidate that can benefit from a similar refactoring is the [`BaseVMState.make_receipt`](https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/73662176575c82f64be26ccda91a1e7b34fb0a99/evm/vm_state.py#L306) method. This method is currently called inside [`BaseVMState.add_transaction(transaction, computation, block)`](https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/73662176575c82f64be26ccda91a1e7b34fb0a99/evm/vm_state.py#L253), though receipt generation has nothing to do with adding the transaction to a block. A better place to make the call is in [`BaseTransactionExecutor.execute_transaction`](https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/73662176575c82f64be26ccda91a1e7b34fb0a99/evm/vm_state.py#L359). It therefore  also makes logical sense to move `BaseVMState.make_receipt` to the [`BaseTransactionExecutor`](https://github.com/ethereum/py-evm/blob/73662176575c82f64be26ccda91a1e7b34fb0a99/evm/vm_state.py#L358) class, which has all the necessary information for receipt generation, i.e. vm state (via `self`), `computation`, and `transaction`.
### How can it be fixed

1. Add `make_receipt` as an `abstractmethod` to `evm.vm_state.BaseTransactionExecutor`.
2. Move the call to `self.make_receipt` in the `evm.vm_state.BaseVMState.add_transaction`, to `evm.vm_state.BaseTransactionExecutor.execute_transaction`.
3. Implement `make_receipt` in `evm.vm.forks.frontier.vm_state.FrontierTransactionExecutor`.
4. Use proper inheritance in other forks, notably in `ByzantiumVMState`.",{},{}
