13202,IssuesEvent,2017-09-25 16:16:21+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,opened,Expired repo token(s) preventing the addition of new channels to Conda config,[],[],0,"After adding channels to `.condarc`, I was getting the following errors from `conda install` & `conda search`:

> Fetching package metadata ...
> CondaHTTPError: HTTP 401 UNAUTHORIZED for url <https://conda.anaconda.org/bioconda/osx-64/repodata.json>
> Elapsed: 00:00.343158
> CF-RAY: 3a32a0579b4a4716-EWR
> 
> The remote server has indicated you are using invalid credentials for this channel.
> 
> If the remote site is anaconda.org or follows the Anaconda Server API, you
> will need to
>   (a) remove the invalid token from your system with `anaconda logout`, optionally
>       followed by collecting a new token with `anaconda login`, or
>   (b) provide conda with a valid token directly.
> 
> Further configuration help can be found at <https://conda.io/docs/config.html>.
> 

I saw no change after running `anaconda logout`, but removing the new channels from `.condarc` worked (I saw the behavior with `conda-forge` & `bioconda` specifically). 

I found this issue: https://github.com/conda/conda/issues/5873, and followed @kalefranz's recommendation of running `python -m conda.gateways.anaconda_client`. That gave me:

> {u'https://api.anaconda.org': '<TOKEN>', u'http://repo.demo.continuum.io/api': '<TOKEN>', u'http://repo.demo.continuum.io/conda': '<TOKEN>', u'https://conda.anaconda.org': '<TOKEN>'}

Again following the recommendation in the issue thread, I set  `add_anaconda_token` to false. That fixed the problem.

I have two questions:

- What types of other problems (if any) can I expect from  setting `add_anaconda_token` to false?
- Is this something anyone using Anaconda long enough to have expired tokens on their machine is going to encounter? I believe @bkreider ran into this as well. 

cc: @ContinuumIO/implementation_engineers @ContinuumIO/sales-engineering ",{},{}
