13258,IssuesEvent,2017-05-08 16:36:32+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Support different versions of a package not conflicting,"[{'id': 91066590, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/1%20-%20Backlog/long%20term', 'name': '1 - Backlog/long term', 'color': 'FFFFFF', 'default': False}, {'id': 75417446, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/priority:low', 'name': 'priority:low', 'color': 'cccccc', 'default': False}, {'id': 567981139, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/reso:wontfix', 'name': 'reso:wontfix', 'color': '1d76db', 'default': False}, {'id': 16544532, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type:feature', 'name': 'type:feature', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],1,"There are a few packages that I know of that have a major version bump that is backwards incompatible, so they allow installing both concurrently. GMP, gmpy (which named its second version gmpy2 to get around this issue), and QT (I think) are examples of this. The only way to support this currently is to name the package with a version number, like gmp4 and gmp5.

