I am using calling conda from python, creating and deleting environment repeatedly.

## Current Behavior
<!-- What actually happens?
     If you want to include console output, please use ""Steps to Reproduce"" below. -->
Conda uses ""vcruntime140.dll"" from partially-deleted environments.

### Steps to Reproduce
<!-- If the current behavior is a bug, please provide specific, minimal steps to independently reproduce.
     Include the exact conda commands that reproduce the issue and their output between the ticks below. -->

1. create an environment containing any package (semantic_version is a small package)
```
$ conda create -p c:\temp\test semantic_version -y
Solving environment: done

## Package Plan ##

  environment location: c:\temp\test

  added / updated specs:
    - semantic_version


The following NEW packages will be INSTALLED:

    certifi:          2018.8.13-py36_0
    pip:              10.0.1-py36_0
    python:           3.6.6-hea74fb7_0
    semantic_version: 2.6.0-py36_0
    setuptools:       40.0.0-py36_0
    vc:               14.1-h0510ff6_3
    vs2015_runtime:   15.5.2-3
    wheel:            0.31.1-py36_0
    wincertstore:     0.2-py36h7fe50ca_0

Preparing transaction: done
Verifying transaction: done
Executing transaction: done
#
# To activate this environment, use
#
#     $ conda activate c:\temp\test
#
# To deactivate an active environment, use
#
#     $ conda deactivate
```
2. Just open an interpreter in the base environment
```
(base) User@WINDOWSQA-PC C:\Users\User
$ python
Python 3.6.4 |Anaconda custom (64-bit)| (default, Jan 16 2018, 10:22:32) [MSC v.1900 64 bit (AMD64)] on win32
Type ""help"", ""copyright"", ""credits"" or ""license"" for more information.
>>>
```

3. In another shell, try to manually delete the environment
```
$ rd /s /q c:\temp\test
c:\temp\test\vcruntime140.dll - Access is denied.
```

This DLL is the only file left in the environment.
4. Close the interpreter.

- The environment no longer appears in ""conda env list""

```
$ conda env list
# conda environments:
#
base                  *  C:\Users\User\Anaconda3
```

In this stage, the DLL can be deleted, but only if the interpreter is closed - re-opening it and trying to delete again gives the same error as before.
This, together with the following error, means the invalid environment can not be deleted programmatically from Python.
5. Try to remove the environment:
```
$ conda env remove -p c:\temp\test -y

EnvironmentLocationNotFound: Not a conda environment: c:\temp\test

```
## Expected Behavior
<!-- What do you think should happen? -->
If the environment is considered invalid, conda should not hold the DLL on startup.

