13505,IssuesEvent,2018-03-20 00:59:13+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,closed,"""filtertype: kibana"" does not work with Kibana indexes migrated from 5.x to 6.x",[],"[{'login': 'untergeek', 'id': 1020383, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/1020383?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/untergeek', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"### Expected Behavior
`filtertype: kibana` should match `.kibana-6` index with `.kibana` alias.

### Actual Behavior
`filtertype: kibana` does not match `.kibana-6` index with `.kibana` alias.

### Steps to Reproduce the Problem
  1. Run steps 2 and 4 from [Migrating Kibana index to 6.0][1]
  1. Run an action with `filtertype: kibana` (E.g. `curator_cli  show_indices --filter_list '{""filtertype"":""kibana""}'`)
  1. `.kibana-6` should be excluded

### Specifications

  - Version: Curator 5.4.0, ES+Kibana 6.2.2
  - Platform: [Docker][2]

## Context (Environment)
We migrated our Kibana index according to the [Migrating Kibana index to 6.0][1] guide. Using `filtertype: kibana` no longer works after the migration. This is likely because the actual index was renamed to `.kibana-6` and `.kibana` is now an alias, not an index.

## Detailed Description
The filter should either include indexes with a suffix after the initial `.kibana`, or it should also match any index pointed to by the `.kibana` alias.

As a workaround we're using:
```
- filtertype: pattern
  kind: regex
  value: '^\.kibana.*$'
```

[1]: https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/kibana/current/migrating-6.0-index.html
[2]: https://hub.docker.com/r/bobrik/curator/",{},{}
13512,IssuesEvent,2017-03-27 21:40:18+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,closed,Can't delete_indices by monthly,[],[],4,"I have no idea why it adds a '1'.

```python
def get_datetime(index_timestamp, timestring):
    """"""
    Return the datetime extracted from the index name, which is the index
    creation time.

    :arg index_timestamp: The timestamp extracted from an index name
    :arg timestring: An strftime pattern
    :rtype: :py:class:`datetime.datetime`
    """"""
    # Compensate for week of year by appending '%w' to the timestring
    # and '1' (Monday) to index_timestamp
    if '%W' in timestring:
        timestring += '%w'
        index_timestamp += '1'
    elif '%U' in timestring:
        timestring += '%w'
        index_timestamp += '1'
    elif '%m' in timestring:
        if not '%d' in timestring:  #<---------This is what I concerned.
            timestring += '%d'
            index_timestamp += '1'
    return datetime.strptime(index_timestamp, timestring)
```",{},{}
13516,IssuesEvent,2017-05-03 16:06:08+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,closed,Indices with epoch 0 are ignored by curator,"[{'id': 52803247, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/elastic/curator/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ff0040', 'default': True}]","[{'login': 'untergeek', 'id': 1020383, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/1020383?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/untergeek', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",1,"Hi,

I've encountered the following issue:

Assume someone created an index named `shakespeare-1970.01.01`. 
The following filters won't match the index, although it is clearly older than 30 days.:

```json
filters:
- filtertype: pattern
  kind: prefix
  value: shakespeare-
- filtertype: age
  source: name
  direction: older
  timestring: '%Y.%m.%d'
  unit: days
  unit_count: 30
```

The debug-log shows the following message:

`DEBUG  curator.indexlist  filter_by_age:456  Index ""shakespeare-1970.01.01"" does not meet provided criteria. Removing from list.`

Epoch 0 is considered neither older nor newer than any other timestamp so this index will never be deleted.


Thanks for looking into that issue.

Tobi",{},{}
