13768,IssuesEvent,2017-10-06 15:05:34+00:00,39039065,Azure/azure-storage-python,7535975,alfpark,6844498,Azure,opened,Retry callback should provide exception context,[],[],0,"The retry handling logic should provide the **unwrapped** exception context (i.e., the exception that `AzureException` wraps) to the `retry_callback()`. Please see the [affected code](https://github.com/Azure/azure-storage-python/blob/e8472835df490d5bdb035de1a9b424a407a658f5/azure-storage-common/azure/storage/common/storageclient.py#L343).

There does not seem to be a good reason to suppress this information from custom retry handlers and obfuscates why a retry is being called (and thus why an exception was raised for the request). Simply discerning the difference between a `context.response` of `None` as [**always** needing a retry is arbitrary](https://github.com/Azure/azure-storage-python/blob/master/azure-storage-common/azure/storage/common/retry.py#L60-L65) and does not apply to all situations. For example, a connection fault from the lower layer urllib3 of `[Errno -2] Name or service not known` should not be retried, but will always be retried with no way to change this behavior without providing a `try/except` around the actual storage SDK call itself, which defeats the purpose of custom retry handlers wrapping this functionality.

The proposal is to either add the exception context on the `RetryContext` or add an optional parameter to the `retry_callback` function. The former would be a cleaner approach.",{},{}
