14282,IssuesEvent,2017-01-03 11:23:53+00:00,20762263,appressoas/django_cradmin,84501,espenak,7713939,appressoas,closed,Cleanup form styling,[],[],0,"We need:

- Uniform spacing for both simple and complex form fields.
- Handling of help text and error/warning messages for fields.

After some research, I can not see any other option than to introduce a wrapper element around form fields.

## Breaking changes

- The ``label`` class must be changed to not have a large amount of spacing below it. We can do this without breaking too much by adding ``label--spaced`` css class that has ``margin-bottom: $vertical-rythm--spacing;``. So the only required change to existing code will be to add ``label--spaced``.
- Fieldsets must not have any extra spacing. We assume they contain ``label--spaced`` or the new wrapper element, which both provide spacing. If we want fieldset variants with extra spacing, we should add a ``fieldset--spaced`` variant.


## Required changes

- Add ``fieldwrapper`` class that wraps form fields and related elements (help text, warnings, label, ...).
- Add ``help-text`` class for help text.
- Make default spacing uniform. This means ``margin-bottom: $unit`` for ``label`` and ``help-text``.


## Other changes
- We should rename ``error`` to ``message`` (with message--error and message--info variants). Message should have a ``message--compact`` variant that spaces them just like label and help-text (for error and info messages related to form fields).
- We should require class for ``fieldset`` and ``legend``, but move the reset code into _reset.scss.",{},{}
14285,IssuesEvent,2016-09-13 20:19:26+00:00,1199632,schematics/schematics,52256,lkraider,7866441,schematics,opened,Model + Schema,[],[],0,"Hi all,

I am working on making Schematics work with SQLAlchemy (see https://github.com/schematics/schemalchemy module) by bringing calculated types (getter/setter functions) up-to-date.

The core issue is to have the model instance go through the import loop, so that custom user setters can run against the instance.

Towards this goal, I ended up splitting the Model into a simpler structure called Schema, similar to what SQLAlchemy does with its Table vs Base types.

The current work is ongoing in my repo at:
https://github.com/nKey/schematics/tree/calculated-type

What does this mean in practice? The Model now wraps the data and encodes the usual lib workflow, while the Schema encodes the actual type structure. This means any field name can fit into the Schema (no Model method conflict), and people that need more complex usage can rely on the backend without needing a Model.

Example:
```python
    schema = Schema('Player',
        Field('id', IntType()),
        Field('first_name', StringType(required=True)),
        Field('last_name', StringType(required=True)),
        Field('full_name', calculated(
            type=StringType(),
            fget=get_full_name,
            fset=set_full_name))
    )
    input_data = {'id': '1', 'full_name': 'John Doe', 'hi': 1}
    converted_data = convert(schema, input_data, partial=True)
    validated_data = validate(schema, converted_data, convert=False, partial=True)
```

This issue is just a notice I am working on this, it is not ready for a PR and it breaks the API (although I am making compatibility mixins).
",{},{}
