15328,IssuesEvent,2015-05-14 12:47:25+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,reopened,"Preprocessors, data_handlers, validators as schema methods?","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/labels/feedback%20welcome', 'name': 'feedback welcome', 'color': '009800'}]",[],23,"Often, validators and preprocessors only apply to a single `Schema`, so it may make sense to define them within the `Schema`--rather than as separate functions--for better cohesion.

Method names could be passed to `__validators__`, et. al, like so:

```python
class UserSchema(Schema):
    __validators__ = ['validate_schema']

    def validate_schema(self, data):
        # ...
```",{},{}
15331,IssuesEvent,2016-02-01 04:03:32+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,Incorrect implementation of List field deserialization,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/labels/ready%20to%20claim', 'name': 'ready to claim', 'color': '009800'}]",[],8,"Problem explanation:

```python
from marshmallow import Schema, fields, validate, validates, validates_schema, ValidationError


class IntRangeSchema(Schema):
    first = fields.Integer(required=True)
    last = fields.Integer(required=True)


class PoolSchema(Schema):
    name = fields.String(required=True)
    ranges = fields.List(fields.Nested(IntRangeSchema))

    @validates('ranges')
    def validate_ranges(self, ranges):
        print 'validate_ranges %s' % repr(ranges)
```

When I load valid data, the validate_ranges() is called with a list of dictionaries (which is expected):
```python
schema = PoolSchema(strict=True)
data = {
    'name': 'pool1',
    'ranges': [
        {'first': 1, 'last': 10},
        {'first': 11, 'last': 20},
    ],
}
print repr(schema.load(data).data)
# => validate_ranges [{'last': 10, 'first': 1}, {'last': 20, 'first': 11}]
# => {'ranges': [{'last': 10, 'first': 1}, {'last': 20, 'first': 11}], 'name': u'pool1'}
```
But when I load an invalid data, then the validates_ranges() receives only a non-valid dictionary, not a list:
```python
data = {
    'name': 'pool2',
    'ranges': [
        {'first': 1, 'last': 10},
        {'last': 10},
    ],
}            
print repr(schema.load(data).data)
# => validate_ranges {'last': 10}
# => ... ValidationError
```
Moreover, if I add complete schema validation (via ```validates_schema```), this is what passed to it:
```
{'ranges': {'last': 10}, 'name': u'pool2'}
```

I see multiple problems here:
1) naive deserialization in List field type
2) running validations for fields that have already failed by other means.

The second issue is addressed in https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/issues/323, so I'll focus on the first one.

Let's take List field as example. Deserialization of list types is basically:
```python
def _deserialize(self, value, attr, data):
    return [self.container.deserialize(each) for each in value]
```

By definition container is a field type which will report deserialization/validation errors by raise ValidationError exceptions. That means that you will get an error for the first invalid item in the list and the rest of items won't be validated at all. The proper way would be to accumulate all errors:
```python
def _deserialize(self, value, attr, data):
    if not utils.is_collection(value):
        self.fail('invalid')
    result = []
    errors = {}
    for idx, each in enumerate(value):
        try:
            result.append(self.container.deserialize(each))
        except ValidationError as e:
            result.append(e.data)
            errors.update({str(idx): e.message})

    if errors:
        raise ValidationError(errors, data=result)

    return result
```",{},{}
15332,IssuesEvent,2016-02-27 22:33:57+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,802148,Tim-Erwin,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,Dynamically specify 'only' parameter for nested fields,[],[],0,"I'm able to specify the `only` parameter when instantiating a schema (`MySchema(only=('field1', 'field2')`), however, this does not work for nested fields. I'd like to be able to have something like `MySchema(only=('field1', ('field2', ('subfield1', 'subfield3'))))` where *field2* is a nested field of which only *subfield1* and *subfield2* should be serialized.

I'd be willing to implement it, however, first I wanna know if it has a chance to get into marshmallow. Secondly, it seems to not be a straight forward addition; instead of (or additionally to) during instantiation of the nested schema, the *only* parameter needs to be passed when serializing. So I'd appreciate any hints of how to implement this properly.

The motivation behind this are APIs like [JSONAPI](http://jsonapi.org/) which allow to dynamically specify fields like so: `GET /articles?include=author&fields[articles]=title,body&fields[people]=name`. One could argue that resources are not really rendered in a nested fashion in JSONAPI responses. So lets assume, we use a (not yet implemented) `IncludeSchema` instead. That will, however, leave us with the same challenges of specifying the *only* parameter dynamically.",{},{}
15335,IssuesEvent,2017-01-30 09:12:17+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,343998,bow,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,Domain name validation in Email validator,[],[],0,"Hello developers,

This is more of a question (possibly an issue). I was trying to validate some email addresses using the `Email` validator class, when I stumbled on it not validating this particular email address: `test@domain.c`

I then looked into [the code](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/blob/dev/marshmallow/validate.py#L119) and found that the part after the `.` in the domain name must be at least 2 characters.

May I ask what the reasoning behind this is?

I know email validation (and by extension domain name validation) can be a complicated issue, so I tried looking up if there are formal specifications that can be relied upon. I found that the format of the domain name is specified in [this RFC, section 2.1](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1123#page-13) and by extension [this RFC, section B](https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc952.txt). There seems to be no restrictions there on limiting the part after the `.` to 2 characters.

I am on Python 3.5.2, running marshmallow version 2.10.3. Thanks in advance!",{},{}
