15649,IssuesEvent,2016-06-29 20:46:32+00:00,597114,Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper,237980,orbeckst,11325701,Becksteinlab,closed,Gromacs 5.x MDrunner class implementation incompatibilities,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'e11d21'}]","[{'login': 'orbeckst', 'id': 237980, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/237980?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/orbeckst', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/orbeckst/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",2,"I have found two errors in regards to the MDrunner class and the `check_mdrun_success` function found in `run.py`.

1. Command passed to subprocess in the class method `run` does not include `gmx`, resulting in an `OSError`
2. `check_mdrun_success` searches the last couple of lines of the log file for the string `""Finished mdrun on node""` at the start of the line, while a successful run writes `""Finished mdrun on rank""`

My temporary fixes to these were as follows:
1. 
```python
cmd = self.commandline(**mpiargs) 
cmd = ['gmx'] + cmd
```
But this is clearly a sloppy solution while breaking Gromacs 4.x usage
2. Simply change `if line.startswith(""Finished mdrun on node"")` to `if line.startswith(""Finished mdrun on rank"")`",{},{}
15650,IssuesEvent,2018-08-07 19:49:04+00:00,597114,Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper,237980,orbeckst,11325701,Becksteinlab,closed,Test*.test_mdrun failures under Python 3.x,"[{'id': 356470133, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwzNTY0NzAxMzM=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper/labels/Python3', 'name': 'Python3', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],2,"The Gromacs 4.6.5 and 2018.2 tests with Python 3.6 fail (see [#274](https://travis-ci.org/Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper/builds/411547151)), specifically

* TestAmber03star.test_mdrun 
* TestAmber03w.test_mdrun 
* TestCharmm22st.test_mdrun 

(These tests already failed for PR #127 but we merged nevertheless. This issue addresses the required clean up.)


",{},{}
15652,IssuesEvent,2018-01-31 04:19:24+00:00,28774758,ets-labs/python-dependency-injector,2900574,vporton,11329744,ets-labs,closed,Overriding a factory argument,[],[],1,"As I understand, there is no yet the following feature (please add it):

If we add a keyword argument to a factory provider, the keyword should be passed to the constructor of the object (overriding the corresponding arguments passed to the `Factory()` constructor).

```
processes_factory = providers.Factory(Process, logger=default_logger_factory, db=db_factory)
```

Now we would be able to call `processes_factory(logger=send_to_browser)`.

This is especially useful when one has many keyword arguments in `providers.Factory()` and want to change one or several of them without duplicating all unchanged arguments.

Note that for singletons this should throw an exception.

Note that I am a novice in python-dependency-injector. I do not warrant all this is right.",{},{}
