15745,IssuesEvent,2018-02-12 20:04:38+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,"the meaning of unknown in an optimization problem, and intermediate (nonoptimal) solutions. ",[],[],4,"1) If I stop Z3 before termination and get
unknown
(objectives
 (  (66 1039))
)
(model 
...

does this mean that it found a feasible solution (i.e., satisfies all the hard constraints), but not the optimum ? it makes more sense to me that the status should be 'sat' rather than 'unknown'. Perhaps there should be a new status 'sat but not known if optimal'. 

2) could be great to give it the option to print non-optimal solution during run-time. Having the ctrl^c option is not always good enough when it is a long run-time: you do not know whether the solution is good enough to stop the engine or whether it even found a first solution. So while pressing ctrl^c tells you this, it also stops the process. 
A nice interface to this is e.g., the one in cplex. There you can give it a parameter CPX_PARAM_INTSOLFILEPREFIX with the prefix of the solution files that it will emit during the run. ",{},{}
15751,IssuesEvent,2017-02-24 20:58:08+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,177622,dwoos,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,SMT tactic vs. SMT inconsistencies,[],[],0,"My understanding is that `(check-sat-using smt)` should be equivalent to `(check-sat)`. This seems not to always be the case. I've found a couple of examples where they actually return different results (attached here: [z3-tactic-bug.zip](https://github.com/Z3Prover/z3/files/800453/z3-tactic-bug.zip)). For the first test case (`bug1.smt2` and `bug1-tactic.smt2`), `(check-sat)` returns `unknown`, while `(check-sat-using smt)` returns `unsat`. For bug 2 (`bug2.smt2` and `bug2-tactic.smt2`), the situation is reversed (though `(check-sat-using smt)` takes an extremely long time, around 8 minutes on my machine, to return `unknown`.

I ran Z3 with `-v:10` on bug 1, and observed some differences:

Using `(check-sat)`:
```
(smt.simplifier-done)
(smt.simplifier-done)
(smt.searching)
(smt.simplifying-clause-set :num-deleted-clauses 235)
(smt.restarting :propagations 9602 :decisions 421 :conflicts 101 :restart 150 :agility 0.080781)
(smt.simplifying-clause-set :num-deleted-clauses 17)
(smt.giveup quantifiers)
unknown
```

Using `(check-sat-using smt)`:
```
(smt.simplifier-done)
(smt.simplifier-done)
(smt.searching)
(smt.simplifying-clause-set :num-deleted-clauses 36)
(smt.restarting :propagations 7663 :decisions 537 :conflicts 101 :restart 150 :agility 0.0522954)
(smt.simplifying-clause-set :num-deleted-clauses 13)
unsat
```

It seems surprising that simplification is behaving so differently, and I wonder whether this is causing the difference in results.

I'm opening a separate issue about timing differences (`(check-sat-using smt)`) seems to be significantly slower in many cases).",{},{}
15759,IssuesEvent,2017-05-06 00:28:28+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,549449,LeventErkok,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,Retrieving models for pareto objectives,[],[],2,"In https://github.com/Z3Prover/z3/issues/955, you mentioned for pareto, ""one simply issues a check-sat"" command to retrieve the stream of models.

I'm trying to figure out how to do this in practice. I've tried the following:

```
(declare-const x Int)
(declare-const y Int)
(assert (>= 1 x))
(assert (>= x 0))
(assert (>= 1 y))
(assert (>= y 0))
(minimize x)
(maximize (+ x y))
(minimize y)
(set-option :opt.priority pareto)
(echo ""******* 0"")
(check-sat)
(get-model)
(echo ""******* 1"")
(check-sat)
(get-model)
(echo ""******* 2"")
(check-sat)
(get-model)
(echo ""******* 3"")
(check-sat)
(get-model)
(echo ""******* 4"")
(check-sat)
(get-model)
```

But, as far as I can see, z3 prints the exact same model in each of those `check-sat` calls. This does make sense to me since I didn't assert/remove any constraints.

I also tried the following:

```
(set-option :opt.priority pareto)
(check-sat)
(get-value (x) :model_index 0)
(get-value (y) :model_index 0)
(get-value (x) :model_index 1)
(get-value (y) :model_index 1)
```

which did not work either, as it says index is out-of-bounds.

Am I supposed to issue a negated-model before the next check-sat? How does that interact with pareto fronts?",{},{}
15761,IssuesEvent,2017-05-28 21:14:59+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,549449,LeventErkok,11668813,Z3Prover,reopened,"Unexpected output when ""produce-proofs"" is given",[],[],6,"I'm playing with proof-generation features in Z3. For this input:

```
(set-option :produce-models true)
(set-logic QF_FP)
(declare-fun s0 () Int)
(declare-fun s1 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24))
(assert (>= s0 0))
(check-sat)
(get-value (s0))
```

Z3 happily produces:

```
sat
((s0 0))
```

Note that I'm using `QF_FP` for the logic, since I want to mix Integers and Floats. (Is there a logic that ""officially"" combines them? I couldn't find it.)

However, if I insert `(set-option :produce-proofs true)` at the very top, keeping everything else the same:

```
(set-option :produce-proofs true)
(set-option :produce-models true)
(set-logic QF_FP)
(declare-fun s0 () Int)
(declare-fun s1 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24))
(assert (>= s0 0))
(check-sat)
(get-value (s0))
```

I get:

```
sat
((s0 Int!val!0))
```

So, it appears the `(set-option :produce-proofs true)` makes z3 decide to interpret `Int` as an uninterpreted sort in this case.

I think the setting of `QF_FP` can justify that decision, but why doesn't that happen in the original input? Or conversely, if the original is OK, why does setting `:produce-proofs` to `true` cause a different behavior here?

I'm not suggesting this is a bug, but it seems inconsistent.",{},{}
15762,IssuesEvent,2018-05-25 18:02:46+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,Access Duality's counterexample when query fails,[],"[{'login': 'kenmcmil', 'id': 8010069, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/8010069?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/kenmcmil', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kenmcmil/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",1,"I know that one can see the counterexample generated by Duality to refute a query using the option `:print-certificate true` in the `query` command. But is there currently a way to retrieve this as a model over the API? (I'm using OCaml)

I found the function `display_certificate_non_const` in `src/muz/duality/duality_dl_interface.cpp`, which basically does what I want, but it doesn't seem to be exposed over the API and it prints the model as a string instead of returning it. There didn't seem to be any obstacles to writing a function that just returns this model, so I tried it and it works for me. Is this something we can add to the API?",{},{}
