17499,IssuesEvent,2016-12-06 14:58:20+00:00,16865424,pimutils/vdirsyncer,837573,untitaker,17852924,pimutils,closed,Don't repair RFC-conform UIDs by default,"[{'id': 89425606, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pimutils/vdirsyncer/labels/cat:%20ui', 'name': 'cat: ui', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}, {'id': 292790365, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pimutils/vdirsyncer/labels/easy', 'name': 'easy', 'color': '009800', 'default': False}, {'id': 90006607, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pimutils/vdirsyncer/labels/mod:%20DAV', 'name': 'mod: DAV', 'color': '207de5', 'default': False}, {'id': 336204756, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pimutils/vdirsyncer/labels/ready', 'name': 'ready', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}, {'id': 80748616, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pimutils/vdirsyncer/labels/type:%20bug', 'name': 'type: bug', 'color': 'eb6420', 'default': False}]",[],4,"Why is @ not in the list of safe chars for UIDs? (See PR #231.) If one follows the RFC's recommendations (see https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5545#section-3.8.4.7), then an @ is bound to be there. Now what happens when doing a repair, e.g., due to some duplicate UID, then almost all entries will have their UID changed. In case the entry creator used a creation date as the start of the UID (as recommended), this actually causes convenient info to be lost. Namely, if one looks at the entries in the directory listing, one won't be able to use a nice ordering.

I'd like to request putting @ in the list of safe chars for UIDs.

I'm aware that @ is a reserved character and that means that in principle it should be encoded in URLs, but this consideration should not affect restrictions imposed on the UID.",{},{}
17514,IssuesEvent,2016-06-10 22:41:47+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,opened,Interactive webroot values not stored in renewal config file,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/Urgent', 'name': 'Urgent', 'color': 'ff0000'}]",[],0,"This is due to using mutable values as the default in `argparse` such as `list` and `dict` and then reaching inside `argparse` to check the defaults in `storage.py`. The result is modifications to these values also modify the default, meaning they always compare equal to the default value and `storage.py` thinks they should not be saved.",{},{}
