18025,IssuesEvent,2016-10-04 13:53:26+00:00,66363927,zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient,8939758,andy-maier,21196715,zhmcclient,opened,Issues with the design of zhmcclient exceptions,[],[],0,"Several issues:

1. We wrapper some exceptions into zhmcclient exceptions, but loose information. That is the case for:

   * AuthError - we create that for any HTTP status 403, and loose the details returned by the HMC.
   * ConnectionError - while we include the message of the underlying exception in the message of the ConnectionError, we loose details that could be machine-processible such as the socket errno number etc.

2. We do not raise the following exceptions at all, currently:

   * ParseError
   * VersionError

   Need to revisit whether we want them to be raised.

3. The zhmcclient methods mostly repeat the zhmcclient exceptions in their Raises: definition. Can we simplify that.

4. The zhmcclient Python properties can raise exceptions but do not document that at all currently.",{},{}
18029,IssuesEvent,2016-09-08 21:05:53+00:00,66363927,zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient,8939758,andy-maier,21196715,zhmcclient,closed,CpcManager does not expose its parent in the resource tree,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient/labels/area:%20code', 'name': 'area: code', 'color': '207de5'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient/labels/resolution:%20no%20issue', 'name': 'resolution: no issue', 'color': 'cccccc'}]",[],1,"The `CpcManager´ class takes a `Client` object as input that defines its scope and acts as its parent in the resource tree, but it has no `client` property that allows navigating back to that parent. This is inconsistent with all other resource classes, which allow navigating back to their parent resource.

In this case, admittedly the parent `Client` is not a resource, but because it acts as a root for navigating the resource tree, the client takes on the role of a parent for the CPC.

Proposal: Add a `client` property to `CpcManager`.",{},{}
18036,IssuesEvent,2016-12-31 13:17:08+00:00,66776276,python-social-auth/social-core,91022,omab,21279195,python-social-auth,closed,Optional deb/C dependencies,[],[],1,"@omab In https://github.com/python-social-auth/social-core/commit/25ca1f51b1e2e22521fdee33ac542ce2bcfb4da0  you have added new dependence `pyjwkest`. With this new requirement every `python-social-auth` user [has to install](https://pycryptodome.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/installation.html#linux-ubuntu) `Cryptodome` with `build-essential libgmp3-dev python3-dev` debian packages (more than 50mb). 

Is it possible to use `extras_require` in `setup.py` to download that kind of dependencies optionally?",{},{}
18049,IssuesEvent,2018-08-09 19:45:40+00:00,72477752,pulumi/pulumi,1871912,swgillespie,21992475,pulumi,closed,Resources from `.get` and refresh interact poorly,[],"[{'login': 'swgillespie', 'id': 1871912, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE4NzE5MTI=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/1871912?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/swgillespie', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"`refreshSourceIterator` constructs goal states for every resource in your snapshot. If any of them are marked `External`, `refreshSourceIterator` drops the `External` bit before sending the event to the engine. The end result is that resources that were `External` get replaced and become non-`External`, which can cause engine crashes later on.

The engine should be smart about this and refresh an `External` resource by reading it again.",{},{}
